  SECTION 4 — PROTECTED INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The following elements of the Software are explicitly protected and may NOT
be reproduced, adapted, extracted, repackaged, used to train or benchmark a
competing system, or used as the basis for any other work without written
permission, even for non-commercial purposes:

  4.1 RUNCARD PROCESS CONTENT AND TEMPLATE LIBRARY
      • The Runcard process flow content, including PGaN-EVG step templates,
        alignment key etch, p-GaN etch, deep mesa etch, active region implant,
        ohmic metal, insulator oxide, gate metal, passivation etch, pad metal,
        and related semiconductor process modules;
      • The selected step names, sequencing, grouping, source rows, notes,
        machine assignments, condition text, inspection points, and retained
        parameter values that encode process know-how;
      • The curated COT-DEV, Etch, Clean, and Rework recipe relationships and
        how they attach to runcard steps;
      • The domain-specific runcard cleanup rules, including hiding parameters
        when a recipe is already recorded, selectively retaining protected
        parameter entries, and structuring inspection/measurement rows.

  4.2 PLATFORM DATA MODEL AND SCHEMA
      • The window.RUN_CARD_DATA schema and its organization into sections,
        steps, photoRecipes, cleanRecipes, referenceSheets, rework flows,
        recipe aliases, and conflict notes;
      • The normalized step schema {id, sourceRow, no, name, recipe, params,
        machine, condition, note, type, enabled} and the card schema containing
        selectedRecipeId, linkedEtchRecipes, linkedCleans, linkedReworks, and
        user-customizable steps;
      • The recipe linkage model that allows COT-DEV selection, multiple Etch
        recipes, multiple Clean recipes, and multiple Rework recipes to be
        attached to a runcard card without destroying the base template;
      • The mapping between original spreadsheet/reference sheet content and
        interactive builder data structures.

  4.3 THREE-PANEL RUNCARD BUILDER ARCHITECTURE
      • The three-column application architecture consisting of Step Library,
        central Runcard Builder, and Recipe Browser panels;
      • The independent scroll-region layout for left, center, and right panels
        while preserving a fixed topbar and active-card workflow;
      • The active-card pager model for editing one runcard card at a time,
        including drag/copy/delete/restore row management and linked recipe
        presentation below the editable step table;
      • The UI/UX logic separating COT-DEV selection, Etch recipes, Clean
        recipes, and Rework recipes into distinct browser tabs and card-level
        action buttons.

  4.4 COT-DEV / ETCH / CLEAN / REWORK RECIPE SYSTEM
      • The COT-DEV recipe application pipeline that replaces photo process
        blocks while preserving exposure steps and selected recipe state;
      • The Track vs Manual COT-DEV mode system, including UI color-coding,
        selected recipe display, and Change workflow;
      • The Etch recipe parser and browser model that reads tabular reference
        sheet entries into grouped recipe parameter tables;
      • The Clean and Rework recipe systems, including their card browser
        display, continuous multi-add behavior, linked recipe rendering, and
        per-card removal controls;
      • The Rework flow library, including PFI38/PFI89 and LOR + PFI38
        variants for No Metal / No Oxide, Metal / No Oxide, Oxide / No Metal,
        and Metal + Oxide process conditions.

  4.5 EXPORT AND REPORTING WORKFLOW
      • The Excel export workflow that generates an index sheet and one sheet
        per runcard card, including selected COT-DEV, Etch, Clean, and Rework
        recipe summaries;
      • The transformation logic from interactive card state to export rows,
        including hidden-parameter handling and linked recipe expansion;
      • The worksheet naming, column sizing, section ordering, and reporting
        structure used to preserve runcard readability.

  4.6 FRONTEND IMPLEMENTATION AND INTERACTION LOGIC
      • The local, single-page runcard authoring interface implemented through
        index.html, src/app.js, and src/styles.css;
      • The state persistence model using browser localStorage and the
        runcard-builder storage namespace;
      • The drag-and-drop template workflow, linked recipe workflow, active
        recipe pending banner, and recipe browser tab system;
      • The specific UX decisions, labels, grouping, and controls that make
        the platform function as a semiconductor runcard builder rather than
        a generic spreadsheet or form editor.

